SIMPLE: embark
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Embark
<hw>Em*bark"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Embarked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Embarking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>embarquer</ets>; pref. <ets>em-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>barque</ets> bark: cf. Sp. <ets>embarcar</ets>, It.
<ets>imbarcare</ets>. See <er>Bark</er>. a vessel.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To cause to go on board a vessel or boat; to put on
shipboard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To engage, enlist, or invest (as persons, money,
etc.) in any affair; <as>as, he <ex>embarked</ex> his fortune in
trade</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It was the reputation of the sect upon which St. Paul
<qex>embarked</qex> his salvation.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embark</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Embark
<hw>Em*bark"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To go on board a
vessel or a boat for a voyage; <as>as, the troops <ex>embarked</ex> for
Lisbon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To engage in any affair.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Slow to <qex>embark</qex> in such an undertaking.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embarkation</ent>⟦br⟧
